Question 5

Write a function called quick_summary which takes two inputs:
x: A numeric vector
group: A factor vector of the same length as x

and produces a list as output which contains the following elements:

missing: The number of missing values in x
means: The means of x for each level of groups.
sds: The standard deviations of x for each level of groups

Hint: When computing the means and standard deviations, you need to exclude missing values using na.rm = TRUE.

quick_summary <- function(x,group){
  
  list_summary <- list()
  
  missing <- sum(is.na(x))
  
  list_summary$missing <- missing
  
  list_summary$means <- tapply(x, group, mean, na.rm = TRUE)
  list_summary$sds <- tapply(x, group, sd, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  return(list_summary)
}

Here is an example of the function in action:

quick_summary(birth_data$weight_pounds, birth_data$is_male)
$missing

$means

7.178759 7.438649 

$sds
   FALSE     TRUE 
1.283197 1.353845

Question 6

Write a function called binary_summary which takes two inputs:

x: A vector containing the values 0 and 1 (possibly NA)
group: A factor vector of the same length as x

and produces a list as output which contains the following elements:

missing: The number of missing values in x
prop: The proportion of 1s in x for each level of groups

binary_summary <- function(x, group){
  
  summary_list <- list()
  
  summary_list$missing <- sum(is.na(x))
  
  summary_list$prop <- tapply(x, group, mean, na.rm = TRUE) 
  
  return(summary_list)
}

Here is an example of the function in action using multiple_births, defined as a binary variable (0 for no and 1 for yes), and is_male:

#First define a new binary variable, multiple_births, using the plurality variable
birth_data$multiple_births <- ifelse(as.factor(birth_data$plurality)==1, 0, 1)

binary_summary(birth_data$multiple_births, birth_data$is_male)
$missing
[1] 27869

$prop
     FALSE       TRUE 
0.02629318 0.02525142

Section 2

Flint is the second poorest city of its size in the United States and has spent six of the past 15 years in a state of financial emergency. One of the cost-cutting measures taken by emergency managers was to stop buying water, sourced from Lake Huron, from the Detroit Water and Sewerage Department. Instead, Flint would use the Flint River for its water supply while waiting for a new pipeline to Lake Huron to be opened. The move was expected to save roughly $5 million over a period of two years.

The Flint River supply was switched on in April 2014. Not long after, problems arose. Flint resident and mother of four LeeAnne Walters noticed that the water coming out of her taps was orange. More worryingly, her familys hair was falling out, her preschool sons had broken out in rashes and one of them had stopped growing.

The orange colour was from iron, but the familys symptoms pointed to a far more dangerous contaminant: lead. (Langkjaer - Bain 2017)

Introduction

The data set consists of 271 homes sampled with three water lead contaminant values at designated time points. The lead content is in parts per billion (ppb). Additionally, some location data is given about each home.

To get started, read in the flint.csv file using the function read.csv, as was done in the ICA with the cereal data. However, you do not need to use the attach function. The data set has five variables:

  • id: sample id number
  • zip: zip code in Flint as to the water samples location
  • ward: ward in Flint as to the water samples location
  • draw: water sample at one of three time points
  • lead: lead content in parts per billion

Before you get started, read The murky tale of Flints deceptive water data by Langkjaer - Bain (2017).

flint <- read.csv("flint.csv")
flint

Question 8

One way to detect outliers in a dataset is with z-scores. The z-score of a data value \(x\) belonging to a sample with mean \(\overline{x}\) and standard deviation \(s\) is \(\frac{x - \overline{x}}{s}\), and it represents the number of standard deviations the data value is from the mean.

Group the data by draw and add a new variable to the data set representing the z-score of the lead values in each draw. Check the reference file to see whether the observations match.

flint_zscores <- flint %>%
  group_by(draw) %>%
  mutate(z_score = (lead - mean(lead, na.rm = TRUE)) / sd(lead, na.rm = TRUE))

flint_zscores

How many z-scores exceed three in absolute value for each draw?

outlier_counts <- flint_zscores %>%
  filter(abs(z_score) > 3) %>% 
  group_by(draw) %>%
  summarise(outlier_count = n())

outlier_counts

Question 9

Based on your analysis in questions 1-8, does it seem that flushing the water decreases the lead content? You may include further code and visualizations.

Flushing appears to reduce lead content in the water, as shown by the decreasing mean, median, and 85th percentile lead levels from the First Draw to the Third Draw. The number of extreme outliers also drops in later draws, suggesting that for most households, flushing helps lower lead exposure. However, some locations, like zip 48504, still show high lead levels even after flushing, indicating that in certain cases, flushing alone may not be enough. # Essential details
